        {
            "review_id": "225294576",
            "steam_id": "76561199815083509",
            "playtime_minutes": 14772,
            "voted_up": true,
            "votes_up": 1,
            "weighted_score": 0.523809552192688,
            "steam_purchase": true,
            "review_text": "Soundpad – The Essential Soundboard for Voice Chat Chaos\n\nOverview\nSoundpad is a lightweight Windows application developed by Leppsoft that allows you to play audio files directly through your virtual microphone . In simple terms, it lets you play sounds, music, or voice clips into any voice chat — Discord, TeamSpeak, in-game chat, Zoom, you name it . Priced at $4.99 on Steam, it has become the go-to tool for streamers, content creators, and anyone who wants to add some humor to their gaming sessions .\n\nStrengths\n\n· Works Everywhere. Soundpad functions as a virtual audio device. Any program that accepts a microphone input can receive your soundboard — games, communication apps, streaming software .\n· Customizable Hotkeys. Assign any sound to any key combination (F1-F12, Ctrl+Key, etc.). During gameplay, you trigger sounds instantly without alt-tabbing .\n· Built-in Recorder and Editor. Record audio directly within the app and trim clips to exact lengths. No need for external audio editing software .\n· Simple Interface. Drag and drop MP3, WAV, or other audio files directly into the application. Organize sounds into folders and groups. The interface is intuitive and easy to navigate .\n· Affordable. At $4.99, it is cheap enough that most users consider it a no-brainer purchase . There is also a free trial version so you can test before buying .\n· Lightweight on Modern PCs. On decent hardware, Soundpad runs smoothly in the background without causing lag or performance issues .\n\nWeaknesses\n\n· Windows Only. No Mac, Linux, or console versions. This is a dealbreaker for many potential users .\n· Initial Setup Can Be Tricky. Configuring Soundpad to work correctly with your specific microphone, communication apps, and Windows audio settings takes some effort. Beginners often need to watch YouTube tutorials .\n· No Built-in Sound Library. You must provide your own audio files. This means downloading MP3s from external sites or recording sounds yourself, which takes time .\n· Can Break Easily. Some users report that Soundpad stops working after Windows updates or certain application changes. Reconfiguration is sometimes required .\n· Resource Usage on Low-End PCs. On older or budget computers, Soundpad can consume noticeable CPU power, potentially causing stutters in games .\n· Volume Control Is Awkward. You cannot easily tell exactly how loud your sounds are to others. Fine-tuning requires guesswork or external testing .\n· DRM Limitation. Soundpad requires disabling Windows Audio DRM, which means you cannot play DRM-protected content (some streaming services) through the application .\n· Can Annoy Your Friends. The software is so effective at trolling that your friends might mute you or stop playing with you. Use responsibly .\n\nTechnical Notes\nThe application runs on Windows 7, 8, 10, and 11. Installation requires a system restart . There is no official Linux version, and workarounds using compatibility layers are not officially supported .\n\nFinal Verdict\nSoundpad is exactly what it promises: a simple, affordable soundboard that works. It is not glamorous, the setup takes patience, and the manual audio sourcing is a minor inconvenience. But once configured, it is reliable, effective, and adds genuine fun to voice chats.\n\nDo I recommend buying it?\nYes, absolutely. It is one of the most useful $5 tools for anyone who regularly uses voice chat while gaming or streaming. The free trial lets you verify it works with your setup before spending money. Just be prepared to watch a setup guide and — most importantly — do not overuse it or your friends will mute you.\n\nPerfect for: Streamers, Discord power users, content creators, and anyone who enjoys friendly chaos in multiplayer games."
        },
